Permission for development at this site within the overall Grangegorman Strategic Development Zone (SDZ) of approx. 28.69 Hectare at Grangegorman Dublin 7.  There are a number of Protected Structures within the Grangegorman SDZ.  No works to any of the protected structures within the Grangegorman SDZ is proposed as part of this application.  The specific site of the proposed development comprises approx 0.439ha and is located on the western side of the Grangegorman Lower bounded by St Brendan's Hospital residential wards (permitted for demolition under planning reg ref. 3112/09) to the north and east a Protected Structure (Female House- RPS 3283 Structure19 ) to the south and existing open space areas to the west at St Brendan's Hospital.

The development will consist of a new science research and incubator facility of six storeys in height (approx 27.2m) over part basement including enclosed plant room set back at roof level, overall height 51.65m OD to parapet level to include extractor flues rising to 53.25m OD) Totalling approx 4739 sqm in floor area as follows (basement 202sqm, ground floor 764sqm, first floor 800sqm, second floor 867sqm, third floor 866sqm, fourth floor 816sqm with 424 sqm of enclosed plant at fifth floor level equivalent.  The development will comprise science laboratories, write up areas, offices, seminar, meeting and training rooms, including ancillary areas/rooms and plant areas for solar panels at roof levels.  Permission is also sought for a temporary access road and associated pathways/ landscaping connection to permitted Ivy Avenue to the North and St Brendan's Way to the south (under Dublin City Council Planning reference 3373/12)  as well as all site development works.  It is proposed that foul and surface water drainage connections will connect to infrastructure Permitted under DCC planning Reference 3373/12.  The development will take place entirely within the boundaries of the Grangegorman Strategic Development Zone.

Construction of a new railway station incorporating, 2no 174m long x 3m wide passenger platforms either side of the Sligo to Dublin railway line.  A footbridge spanning the railway connecting the proposed platforms, with 2no staircases and 2no ramps of a  gradient of 1:20.  Platforms to incorporate lighting, CCTV, ticket vending machines, railings, seatings, shelters, commercial advertising, driver operating monitors, public address, customer information signs, directional and station signage.  Construction of a footbridge over the Royal Canal to provide access from Royal Canal Avenue.  Construction of  stepped and ramped access from Ashington Park.  Installation of street lighting to footpaths extending from the proposed access at Ashington Park.  Clearing of existing vegetation between the park and the railway.  Partial demolition of the existing boundary wall and installation of new sections of boundary wall at the ends of the platform.  Landscaping between the park and the rear of the proposed new platform.  Installation of a dedicated pedestrian and cycle path across the park including disabled parking bays at Ashington Park.  Installation of street lighting to bridge over the Royal Canal as well as the immediate vicinity of Royal Canal Avenue where required.  Partial demolition of the existing boundary fence along the canal and installation of new sections of boundary fencing at the ends of the platform.  Landscaping between the canal and the rear of the proposed new platform.  Installation of an ESB kiosk at Royal Canal Avenue. Construction of a Telecoms Equipment room at the eastern end of the proposed platforms with access road from Ratoath Road.  The total works involved cover an area of approx. 2200 sqm of plan area, and approx 20 linear metres of street frontage.

Development at this site within the overall Grangegorman Strategic Development Zone (SDZ), of approx, 28.69 hectares at Grangegorman Lower, Grangegorman, Dublin 7.  The specific site of the proposed development comprises approx.  1.5 Ha and is located on the western side of Grangegorman Lower bounded by HSE facilities to the north, Church of Ireland Chapel ( a protected structure PRS No. 3285) to the south, Grangegorman Lower to the east and playing fields to the west at the former St. Brendan's Hospital.  The development will consist of demolition works, material alterations, and changes of use from healthcare use to education use to structure nos. 17, 19, 20 and 22 (protected structures) as follows:- 

1) 'The Mortuary' - (Structure 17), Single storey building, existing floorspace c. 264sqm. excluding the ESB Substation.  The proposed change of use of Structure 17 (protected structure, RPS. ref. No. 3286) from healthcare to education use.  The proposed material alterations to Structure 17 will consist of the removal of internal partitions, the upgrade of corridors to improve the fire performance, the refurbishment of existing parquet flooring, the provision of new floor finishes, the provision of new mechanical and electrical services, the provision of new toilet facilities to replace the existing, repairs to the roof and roof structure, the refurbishment of the existing timber windows, repointing of the stonework; 

2) 'The Female House' - (Structure 19), Two Storey building, existing floorspace c. 2.733 sqm. (Ground Floor 1572 sqm. and First Floor 1161 sqm.).  Permission is sought for the demolition of the c. 1970's modern ground floor extension (c. 202 sqm.) to the south west and the boiler house (c. 69 sqm.) at ground floor to the north of the building; the provision of a new entrance to the south side of the building; the proposed change of use of remainder of Structure 19 (protected structure RPS ref. No. 3283) from healthcare to education use.  The proposed material alterations to Structure 19 will consist of internal alterations, which entails the removal of existing partitions, the provision of new internal partitions, the upgrade of corridors, stairs and floors to improve the fire performance, the provision of new floor finishes, the provision of new mechanical and electrical services, the provision of new toilet facilities, the refurbishment of existing windows, repairs to the roof and roof structure, repointing of the stonework. 

3) 'The Male Infirmary' - (Structure 20), Two Storey building, existing floor space c. 496 sqm. (Ground Floor 299 sqm. and First Floor 197 sqm.) Permission is sought for the demolition of modern extensions including the (single storey) block at ground floor to the south west (c. 84 sq); the semi-basement boilerhouse (c. 4 sqm.) and the ground floor toilet block (c. 8 sqm.) to the north of the original building;  the formation of a new entrance door to replace the toilet block on the north side;  the proposed change of use of the remainder of structure 20,  (within the curtilage of R.C. PROTECTED STRUCTURE: For permission for a mixed use development at a site measuring c.0.31 ha at nos. 1-6 Sir John Rogerson's Quay, rear of 3-5 Sir John Rogerson's Quay Nos 16 1/2 and 17 Creighton Street (also known as 16-25) and nos. 21 and 22 Windmill Lane, Dublin 2. The site is bounded generally by Sir John Rogerson's Quay, Creighton Street, Windmill Lane and adjoining building, known as The Observatory on Sir John Rogerson's Quay. The proposed development will consist of the demolition of the existing structures on the site of nos. 1-6 Sir John Rogerson's Quay, with the exception of Nos. 4 and 5 Sir John Rogerson's Quay (both Protected Structures) and the front facade of no. 2 Sir John Rogerson's Quay ( Protected Structure) and the demolition of nos. 16 1/2 and 17 Creighton Street (also known as 16-25) Nos. 21 and 22 Windmill Lane are also proposed to be demolished. The overall area to be demolished is c. 6.500sqm, including 22 no. habitable dwellings. No. 6 Sir John Rogerson's Quay was previously demolished as permitted under Reg. Ref. 1222/03. The development proposes a mixed use development with a total of c. 11,692 sqm GFA comprising a ground floor retail unit (c. 223sqm GFA) accessed from Creighton Street, together with a managed student accommodation complex ( sui generis use) (incorporating the protected structures at nos, 4 and 5 Sir John Rogerson's Quay). The main entrance to the student accommodation complex is proposed off Sir John Rogerson's Quay so as to provide a ground floor foyer, a reception area, leisure/recreational space, and other ancillary accommodation, together with 313 student bedrooms on the upper floors, with communal living/dining accommodation being provided at a variety of locations on the upper floors which incorporate balconies and terraces; a controlled pedestrian/cycle entrance is also proposed off Creighton Street (this will also serve as access in the case of emergencies); Nos 4 and 5 Sir John Rogerson's Quay will be entered independently off Sir John Rogerson's Quay, No. 6 Sir John Rogerson's Quay can also be accessed directly from Sir John Rogerson's Quay. The development proposed is being accommodated in a series of buildings that range in height as follows: part 3 storey's (c. 11.6m); part 4 storey's (c. 15.2m) and part 7 storey's (c. 23.9m) to Sir John Rogerson's Quay (incorporating the facade of No. 2, Nos. 4, 5 and a new infill building at no. 6) 4 storey's (c.15.1-15.9m) to Creighton Street with three storey's above set back off the street (c.23.9-24.6m) and with the corner element to Sir John Rogerson's Quay being 7 storey's (c. 23.9m), and 7 storey's over a lower ground floor (c. 24.6-25.1m) on Windmill Lane internal and external alterations and refurbishment are also proposed at no's 4 and 5 Sir John Rogerson's Quay (both Protected Structures), including the demolition of recent additions at the rear of the buildings and change of use to managed student accommodation; new ground floor facade/front to nos. 4 & 5 Sir John Rogerson's Quay. The facade of no. 2 Sir John Rogerson's Quay (a Protected Structure) is to be refurbished and incorporated into the new building as the main entrance and alterations are proposed to this facade to provide for larger openings, the provision of a canopy structure at the entrance is also proposed together with signage; site development and landscape works are also proposed, including landscaped courtyards, roof terraces, an ESB Sub-Station, delivery and service area off Windmill Lane, bicycle parking facility, a landscaped amenity space set back off Creighton Street. Permission is also being sought for signage in the form of the Urbanest brand which is to be erected on the new building at high level at Sir John Rogerson's Quay (at its corner with Creighton Street) (approx. 1.5m wide x 4.6m high panel, including powder coated aluminium (green) surfaced mounted raised lettering of between 500-700mm high, back lit/halo lit) and also at high level on the corner of Windmill Lane (at its corner with Creighton Street) (approx 4m wide x 1.3m high panel, including powder coated aluminium (green) surface mounted raised lettering of between 400-600mm high, back lit/halo lit). In addition signage is proposed at the main entrance to the student accommodation on the face of the canopy to be located within the new glazed facade of No. 2 Sir John Rogerson's Quay (a Protected Structure); the signage in that case will be in a panel approx. 3m wide x 0.6m high and will contain the Urbanest name and the address of the property.

The application seeks permission to amend a previous permission (Dublin City Council Reg. Ref. 3813/07) that itself amended Reg. Ref. 5616/05 on a smaller site of 0.1024 hectares (called up in the Statutory Notices as no. 25 (part of) to No. 31 York Street and Proud's Lane, Dublin 2) for which Dublin City Council issued an Extension of Duration of Permission (under Reg. ref. 5616/05/x1 on 1st February 2011) to 22nd February 2016. 

Permission Reg. Ref 5616/05 and Reg. Ref 3813/07 collectively permit the construction of a 6 no. storey mixed use building over 4 no. basement levels, and ancillary works on part of this site. The permissions facilitated the provision of the National Surgical Training Centre and a multi-purpose sports hall related activities below ground level. The above floors accommodated a variety of educational, training and commercial uses.

Development on foot of those permissions commenced, comprising site excavation and the construction of basement foundations and retaining walls. Those constructed elements of the permitted development will be modified as appropriate to facilitate their incorporation into the current proposal.

The proposed development will consist of the redesign of the permitted building to develop a six storey educational and medical  training facility over 4 no. basement levels and sub-basement (water tanks and lift pits) accommodating inter alia: multi-purpose sports facilities with related activities and prayer rooms at Basement Levels - 4 and -3; plant room and lower level of raked auditorium including support areas at Basement level -2; auditorium and related break-outs areas and support facilities at Basement Level -1; student foyer area, services desk area, café,kitchen, and ancillary loading area at Ground Floor Level; with 5 no. storeys of educational training and academic support facilities above ground comprising inter alia; library study space; tutorial rooms; practical clinical surgical skills' rooms; other associated ancillary educational facilities; a projecting window at first floor level; the provision of 100 no. bicycle spaces; development of a new electricity substation and plant; external terrace at ground floor level; set back at fifth floor level on the York Street elevation; the relocation of a 375mm public sewer ( with invert levels from 8.57m OD to 8.24OD Malin Head) from underneath the site to Cuffe Street via Cuffe lane; and all associated ancillary works above and below ground including landscape and boundary treatments. An enclosed plant area will be located at 5th floor level, with additional rooftop plant. This structure is used by the patrons of the Odeon Bar and Grill as an outdoor standing/seating area and will be used as a disabled access route into the bar. The top height of the mono-pitch glass canopy is approximately 5.7 metres from ground level and it covers the platform area, which will include the disabled-access platform lift. The development proposed for retention also includes internal storage of approximately 21 square metres at basement level underneath the new platform. This new basement storage includes a lift shaft area for the proposed external disabled-access platform lift mechanism, as well as space for a glass bottle crusher to facilitate on site recycling of the Bar's glass/bottles. This additional basement storage area is accessed from the existing car park/delivery/storage area via a concrete stairs, as well as from a keg hatch in the northern side wall of the new platform structure. A blocked-up opening at basement level in the property's original northern side wall has been reopened to connect this additional storage area through to the property's existing basement storage areas. The development proposed for retention also comprises ancillary works including: a new 1.2 metres wide pedestrian entrance gate from Harcourt Street into the car park/delivery/storage area, with a new section of railing on stone plinth between the existing vehicular gate and the new pedestrian gate which matches the materials of the existing contemporary boundary treatment onto Harcourt Street; the northern end of the building's front steps onto Harcourt Street have been cut back and detailed to symmetrically match the existing arrangement at southern end of the steps (similar to that granted permission as part of Registry Reference 3161/08); a new opening has been cut into the northern side wall of the premises (similar to that granted permission as part of Registry Reference 3161/08) which allows circulation from the front portico area into the new canopy area to the side; a new vertical striped paint effect to the wall and ceiling of the front portico; the re-levelling and resurfacing of the car park/delivery/storage area with cobble-lock paving so the entire car park/delivery/storage area is level with the entrance onto Harcourt Street; a new low planter around the western, northern and eastern boundaries of the car/park/delivery/storage area; and all other ancillary works.

The application site comprises of 0.286 hectares and is bounded to the south by Molesworth Street, to the west by South Fredrick Street, to the North by Setanta Place and to the east by Setanta House and the Protected Structures known as 15 and 16 Molesworth Street and the Freemason's Hall. The development will consist of the demolition of the existing buildings and their replacement with a new office building. The existing buildings consist of a five storey office development with roof plant room level over 2 basement car park levels and include a public house/nightclub to the rear ground and lower ground level, an internal ESB substation and ancillary structures all with a gross floor area of 7,896 sqm (excluding car park areas). The existing car parks have 90 private car park spaces at courtyard and first basement level and 77 public car spaces at the lower basement level linked into the Setanta public car park under Setanta Place. The proposed new development consists of the construction of a six storey office building with roof plant level and with lower ground floor accommodation with a gross floor area of 12,733 sqm all above a double basement car park with a gross floor area of 4,870 sqm. The new building will have 34 private car spaces at basement -1 level and 58 public car space at basement -2 level. In addition there will be 128 no. bicycle parking spaces 2 no. motorcycle spaces, 13 no. showers, changing and locker space and plant space at basement -1 level. The new building includes a terrace setback at fourth and fifth floor levels along Molesworth Street, South Fredrick Street and Setanta Place. The building also includes a terrace at fifth floor level at the corner of Molesworth Street and South Fredrick Street. A pedestrian access point to the new building is proposed from Molesworth Street and another from South Fredrick Street. Service and deliveries will be at an entrance off Setanta Place. The development includes a green roof, an atrium, an ESB sub-station on Setanta Place, an internal landscaped courtyard, site development works, hard and soft landscaping and all other ancillary works. Vehicular access to the private basement car park is proposed from Setanta Place in the same location as the existing vehicular access. A cycle access is provided adjacent to the proposed vehicular access. The new public car park will be accessed through the existing connections at basement -2 level under Setanta Place.

PROTECTED STRUCTURE: Permission for development on lands (0.253ha) at 1,2,3,4 and 5, Camden Street Upper, No's 49, 50 and 51 Camden Street Lower, and all sites to the rear addressing Grantham Place, Dublin 2 (including 12 Grantham Place). No's 1,2,3,4 and 5, Camden Street Upper & No's 49, 50 and 51 Camden Street Lower, Dublin 2 are Protected Structures. The development will consist of the following:- Refurbishment/alterations and change of use of existing buildings on the site and construction of new buildings to the rear to provide a hotel development (165 bedrooms) with ancillary public restaurant/ bar, associated ancillary uses and a retail unit. The overall building will comprise a gross floor area of 6,545sqm, of which 2,425sqm is accommodated within the existing buildings and 4,120 sqm is new build. The refurbished existing frontage buildings incorporating No's 1,2,3,4 and 5, Camden Street Upper, and numbers 49, 50 and 51 Camden Street Lower contain 55 bedrooms and involve internal reconfiguration and works to include repair and replacement (where necessary) of existing windows and doorcases/ entrances and railings to the front. The frontage buildings which are to change to hotel use are currently arranged as follows - No's 4/5 Camden Street Upper (former stain glass manufacturers, now vacant). No's 2/3 Camden Street Upper (formerly commercial offices, now vacant), No's 1/49/50 Camden Street Upper, Camden Street Lower (formerly hotel / commercial and currently used as a hostel), No 51 Camden Street Lower (formerly residential over ground floor commercial, now vacant). 3no. new interconnections are proposed which will mean that the 8 buildings fronting Camden Street Upper / Camden street Lower will be interconnected. The main entrance to the hotel lobby, reception and hotel bar / lounge area is proposed at No. 49 Camden Street Lower. The development involves works and change of use of the chapel building ( currently used as a gym/boxing club) and associated annexes to the rear of No. 49/50 Camden Street Lower to accommodate the hotel / restaurant and ancillary areas. A shop unit (21.8sq.m) with independent street access is proposed at No. 4 Camden Street Upper. The new build element is located to the rear is located to the north and south of the chapel building with a new link building connecting to the rear of No. 49 Camden Street Lower. 2 new external landscaped courtyard spaces are provided on either side of the link building to the rear of No's 1-5 Camden Street Upper and No's 50/51 Camden Street Lower respectively. The new building contains 110 hotel bedrooms and ancillary accommodation over 5 levels (including a lower ground floor level or semi-basement). The new buildings are stepped back from the site boundary on Grantham Place and the internal courtyard and the new building line is also set back from the existing site boundary on Grantham Place. A terrace is provided for 6 bedrooms at third floor level overlooking the central courtyard. No on-site parking is proposed. Vehicular access/egress for the purposes of deliveries and servicing will be via Grantham Place and include an off-street loading area. 17no. cycle parking spaces are provided off Grantham Place. Works to the rear of the existing front buildings (No's 1-5 Camden Street Upper and No's 49-51 Camden Street Lower) will include demolition of remnants of existing extensions and existing lift shaft, repairs/replacement of windows and brickwork cleaned and repointed as required. With the exception of the chapel which is to be refurbished, a number of existing buildings on Grantham Place (including property known as 12 Grantham Place and structures annexed to the chapel located to the rear of 50 and 51 Camden Street Lower) are to be demolished. A new ESB substation is contained within the new building with independent access from Grantham Lane. Permission is also sought for landscaping, plant, signage and all ancillary and associated site development works.

Remodelling of Eaton House (existing office building)Eaton Industries (Ireland) Limited intends to apply for permission for development on this site of 0.198 ha,
approximately, at Eaton House (formerly known as Old brook House), Nos. 24-32 (even) Pembroke Road, Dublin
4.
The development will consist of the remodelling of Eaton House (an existing office building being part 3-storey (Block A) and part 5-storey (with a roof-top plant room acting as a part sixth-storey) (Block B) over basement /lower ground level undercroft) consisting of: the demolition of 180 sq m (169 sq m roof-top plant area and 11 sq m of a portion of the existing stair core) and the construction of 165 sq m new floor area (104 sq m at basement / lower ground level undercroft; 10 sq m at ground level; 10 sq m at first floor level; 10 sq m at second floor level; 4 sq m at third floor level; 4 sq m at fourth floor level; and 23 sq m at roof level), resulting in a building with a total gross floorspace of 3,967 sq m (excluding 990 sq m basement / lower ground level undercroft car parking area, but including an existing electricity substation of 27 sq m) representing a net reduction of 15 sq m in the gross floorspace of the building.
The development will also consist of: the removal, redesign and replacement of all existing facades; the
demolition of the enclosed roof-top plant room, and its replacement with a roofless screened plant area; the
installation of a transparent canopy at the pedestrian entrance to Pembroke Road; alterations to the entrance steps at Pembroke Road, including the provision of a ramp to facilitate disability access and new hard and soft landscaping; alterations to the podium at entrance / ground floor level, including the removal of an existing vehicular ramp, partial infilling of associated opening and the provision of a landscaped courtyard; the remodelling and extension (by some 104 sq m) of the basement / lower ground level undercroft accommodation to provide reconfigured stairs, toilets, showers and associated ancillary accommodation (the car park-related area reduces from 1,089 sq m to 990 sq m at this level); alterations to the existing boundary treatments and landscaping, including the removal of existing plywood sheeting, railing and brickwork facing to an existing wall at the boundary with No. 34 Pembroke Road (a Protected Structure) and an increase in the height of the existing concrete boundary wall by 1.35m; the provision of a corporate sign to the Pembroke Road elevation comprising halo illuminated painted metal letters (measuring 0.617m in height x 2.01m in width) mounted on a stainless steel panel (measuring l.13m in height x 3.34m in width); the installation of a barrier to the car park access from Pembroke Road (including a concrete island and communication stand); the provision of demountable guard rails at roof level; the provision of new boundary railings at Pembroke Road (1.2m in height) and associated gate at the disability access ramp; an increase in the widths of the existing access gates at Baggot Lane and Pembroke Road from 3.06m to 5.00m and from 4.00m to 5.01m, respectively and the provision of a roller shutter to the Pembroke Road vehicular entrance; associated lighting; alterations to existing site servicing (foul and service water drainage) and provision of SUDs' measures, including the installation of an underground rainwater harvesting tank, an attenuation tank and sedum roof to the Pembroke Road frontage (Block A); and all other associated site excavation and site development works above and below ground.
Apart from the demolition, additions and amendments referenced above, the internal reconfiguration of the
building, the reconfiguration of the car parking provision and the provision of bicycle parking and of a recycling area will be carried out as exempted development.

PROTECTED STRUCTURE: RETENTION: Permission for development and Permission for retention of development. At the Mater Misericordiae University hospital complex bounded to the north by the North CircularRoad (NCR), to the west by Berkeley road, to  the south by Eccles Street and to the east by the rear of the terrace of existing houses facing onto Leo Street and by the Mater Private Hospital, Dublin 7.

 The site is approximately  6.2 hectares in area. There  are existing protected structures within the site. No works to any of the protected  structures within the subject site are proposed.

 The proposed development and development proposed to be retained comprises alterations to the permitted 9 storey (10 storey including lift core level) Mater Adult Hospital building which was granted permission by Dublin City Council under planning register reference no. 4929/03, as modified by planning permission register reference nos. 2563/05, 5449/07,2080/08,3013/10 and 3655/10.

This application therefore proposes: 
(a) retention of external amendments to the new adult hospital;

(b) retention of the reconfiguration of internal layouts within the hospital;
 And

(c) proposed development comprising a new sliding gate onto the NCR. 

The total area  of gross floor space which has been added to the new Adult Hospital (as now proposed to be retained) is 395 square metres  (sq. m). In the interests of clarity, this application also seeks to retain 79 sq. m of plant floor area on level 9, which was shown in drawings for  planning application reg. Ref. 2080/08 but which was omitted  from gross  floor space calculations for that application. This application also seeks permission to retain 850 sq. m of floor area (170 sq. m per floor over 5 floors) at the north eastern corner of the 5 storey element of the hospital building which was permitted in reg. Ref. 4929/03 but which was not constructed within the appropriate period in order to facilitate Metro North enabling works (An Bord Pleanala Rail Order Ref. No. 06F.NA0003) to be constructed underneath. The new total gross floor space for the hospital as now proposed to be retained is approximately  55,662 sq. m.

 This planning application therefore proposes in detail:

(a) the retention of the following external works:• addition of 'Mater  Hospital ' signage above NCR entrance canopy (2.43 sq. m); hospital crest on facade of NCR entrance foyer at level 1 (8.61 sq. m); and 2 no. Internally illuminated monolith / pylon signs (3.6 metres (m) tall and 1.2m wide): one of which is located beside the pedestrian entrance on the NCR and the other which is located beside the entrance ramp on Eccles Street

• amendments to lay-by and footpath surface levels on the NCR (in agreement with Dublin City Council's Roads & Traffic Department)

 • addition of an ionic capital sculpture outside the entrance foyer on the NCR

• new gas skid on level 0 at the western delivery yard entrance on the NCR requiring a new compound wall and a 2m wide (approx.) Access gate from the NCR and increased height stone boundary wall and pillar (new height 19.57m ordnance datum (od))

• modification / extension of the VIE gas tank enclosure near the western delivery yard at level 0 including increase in height of permitted VIE tank from 22.87m od to 24.85m od and additional VIE tank (top height approx. 25.57m od)

 • new security hut in the western delivery yard at level 0

• redesigned external vents to basement at level 0 in the eastern service  yard

• omission of vents at level 0 to the east and west of  the permitted 5 storey building element (vent grilles replaced with landscaping)• addition of ventilation louvres at level 0 and omission of privacy louvres at levels 5 and 6 in the building's northern elevation (facing the NCR)

 • reconfiguration of fenestration and access at level 0 of the eastern elevation (waste / service yard) 

• addition of smoke vents in landscaped  roof of NCR entrance foyer and associated landscaping amendments

• modification to glazed roof and enclosure of pavilion on the landscaped  roof of NCR entrance foyer

 • reconfiguration of planting area on level 0 and decking area on level 1, and relocation of smoke vent shaft all in the  courtyard between the new building and the existing phase 1a building 

• reduction in size and revised design of canopies in the ambulance yard at level 0• revised accident and emergency (A&E) vehicular access arrangements, modified forecourt and associated landscaping works

• amendment to the permitted 3 lane vehicular ramp design from Eccles street as per reg. Ref. 3655/10 to a 2 lane vehicular access ramp layout,  omission of pergola over the ramp and relocation of previously permitted  security hut on Eccles street 

• retention of pharmacy compounding unit / clean room in the western delivery yard at level 0, including reduction of basement area below and  associated changes to the surrounding yard area at level 0

• reduction of lift-lobby b2 at level 0 to avoid interference with foundation  of existing building• modified roof shape from sloped to flat over lift shaft  / lift entrance in the western delivery yard at level 0 and addition of canopy outside vehicle goods lift
